    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_2595031243" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2595031243" />
    <a title="Ann" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/90972-ann"><img alt="Ann" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1180465013p2/90972.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/2595031243?book_show_action=true">Nov 15, 2018</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Ann" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Ann" href="/user/show/90972-ann">Ann</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2595031243" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer678409058995873709">Thought I&apos;d read all Chaim Potok&apos;s books, but recently found this one on a library shelf. It is a significant departure from Potok&apos;s other books. He generally tells stories about Jews and Judaism in it&apos;s different forms; this one is about an elderly Korean couple fleeing the horrors of the Korean War. It is a fascinating window into Korean culture and religion, as he walks us through day after painful day of their tortuous flight. They find a critically wounded adolescent boy, and the wife makes</span>
  <span id="freeText678409058995873709" style="display:none">Thought I'd read all Chaim Potok's books, but recently found this one on a library shelf. It is a significant departure from Potok's other books. He generally tells stories about Jews and Judaism in it's different forms; this one is about an elderly Korean couple fleeing the horrors of the Korean War. It is a fascinating window into Korean culture and religion, as he walks us through day after painful day of their tortuous flight. They find a critically wounded adolescent boy, and the wife makes it her mission to save him, while the husband hates the boy and is filled with resentment toward him. It is dark and grim with little redeeming value, except in the dogged determination and love of the wife in the face of overwhelming adversity. <br /><br />Potok is a master storyteller, and I was, as always, drawn into his story. It was not an enjoyable read, but it was an important one. I learned about another culture and came face to face with the dreadful and repugnant acts of war, its effects, and aftermath. I was reminded on every page of the desperate plight of unregenerate mankind, and made acutely aware that the only answer is Jesus. People need the Lord.</span>
  <a data-text-id="678409058995873709" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


