        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3760222190" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer8650425540610868352">Chaim Potok&apos;s omniscient narrator floats like a spirit seamlessly from character to character, sometimes in a flood of stream-of-conscious memory and emotion, in this bleak novel. <br/>The themes of survival and attachment are what kept me flying through its pages, despite the dark setting of war and and poverty. <br/>I&apos;ve read Potok&apos;s Asher Lev novels, and like those stories, we see a fascinating collision of ancient tradition and religion with encounters with Christ and modern Christian culture. <br/>While i</span>
  <span id="freeText8650425540610868352" style="display:none">Chaim Potok's omniscient narrator floats like a spirit seamlessly from character to character, sometimes in a flood of stream-of-conscious memory and emotion, in this bleak novel. <br />The themes of survival and attachment are what kept me flying through its pages, despite the dark setting of war and and poverty. <br />I've read Potok's Asher Lev novels, and like those stories, we see a fascinating collision of ancient tradition and religion with encounters with Christ and modern Christian culture. <br />While it's no feel-good read, the characters and questions it poses about faith and God's unfathomable work of redemption on Earth will stick with me. <br />Four stars only for the grim tone.</span>
